ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The Lincolnshire placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Hearra</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i>. The Northamptonshire derives from an Old English personal name <i>Hǣthhere</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Herendeen  .","Irish: adopted as an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hArrachtáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Arrachtán</i>’, a personal name from a diminutive of <i>arrachtach</i> ‘mighty, powerful’.","Irish: in Kerry, this name was adopted as an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hIongardail</b>, later <b>Ó hUrdáil</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Iongardal</i>’, a personal name of uncertain origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Herington","meanings":["English: variant of   Harrington   or   Herrington  ."]},{"name":"Herrington","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Heronden in Tenterden (Kent) or Herrington in Houghton (Durham). The Kent placename may derive from an Old English personal name <i>Hȳra</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>denn</i> ‘pasture’, while the Durham placename may come from Old English <i>hæring</i> ‘rocky place’ (from <i>hær</i> ‘rock, heap of stones’ + the placename forming suffix <i>-ing</i>) or <i>hæren</i> ‘rocky’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’.","variant of   Harrington  ."]},{"name":"Herendeen","meanings":["Altered form of English   Harrington  ."]},{"name":"Arrington","meanings":["English:","variant of   Harrington   with loss of initial <i>H-</i>.","possibly a habitational name from Arrington, a place in Cambridgeshire, named from an Old English byname, <i>Earn(a)</i>, meaning ‘eagle’ + <i>-inga-</i> ‘people or followers of’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":1,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705201,"age":95,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":104,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Harrington was born in 1454, in England. She married Richard Preston about 1479, in Staverton, Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1454–":"1454–Surnud","1454–Male":"1454–Surnud","1480–1529":"1480–1529","1454–Female":"1454–Surnud","1558":"1558","1455":"1455","1454":"1454","about 1479":"umbes 1479","1480":"1480","1529":"1529","1549":"1549","England":"England","Staverton, Devon, England":"Staverton, Devon, England"},"fi":{"1454–":"1454–Kuollut","1454–Male":"1454–Kuollut","1480–1529":"1480–1529","1454–Female":"1454–Kuollut","1558":"1558","1455":"1455","1454":"1454","about 1479":"noin 1479","1480":"1480","1529":"1529","1549":"1549","England":"England","Staverton, Devon, England":"Staverton, Devon, England"},"fr":{"1454–":"1454–Décédée","1454–Male":"1454–Décédé","1480–1529":"1480–1529","1454–Female":"1454–Décédée","1558":"1558","1455":"1455","1454":"1454","about 1479":"environ 1479","1480":"1480","1529":"1529","1549":"1549","England":"Angleterre","Staverton, Devon, England":"Staverton, Devon, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Agnes Harrington est née en 1454, à Angleterre. Elle a épousé Richard Preston environ 1479, à Staverton, Devon, Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"1454–":"1454–Verstorben","1454–Male":"1454–Verstorben","1480–1529":"1480–1529","1454–Female":"1454–Verstorben","1558":"1558","1455":"1455","1454":"1454","about 1479":"um 1479","1480":"1480","1529":"1529","1549":"1549","England":"England","Staverton, Devon, England":"Staverton, Devon, England","lifeSummary":"Agnes Harrington wurde 1454 in England geboren. Sie hat um 1479 in Staverton, Devon, England Richard Preston geheiratet. Sie hatten mindestens 1 Tochter."},"ht":{"1454–":"1454–Desede","1454–Male":"1454–Desede","1480–1529":"1480–1529","1454–Female":"1454–Desede","1558":"1558","1455":"1455","1454":"1454","about 1479":"about 1